I suppose so, as I say these - these ladies, they - they were all - as far as I knew quite interesting people. I used to stand - at a - this was a block of flats at Baker Street. And I - we used to have 
to get there sharp in the morning at seven o'clock. And there was railings round - base - bottom part of the flats, and we were running round to the back so it'd be their kitchens. Now this particular lady used to always open her window - and - she'd been
 
- a prostitute. She told us this, or told me. But I could always rely on a - a - a nice cup of tea, and a - her daughter was in college. She was paying for her to be in college. And she was quite a nice person. That was her profession to get - to get easy
 
- well, plenty of money. There was another one I used to have to - we were doing - in Soho, and - these - of course you'd get - we used to - I used to get to know them you see, only by - by their looks. And one come along there regular every afternoon and
 give my boy - 'cos I had mate then - my boy a couple of apples or something like that. And they were very good hearted people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 What other kind of life did you see there, did you see much of very rich people being drunk and disorderly and that type of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 
Well - yes, I did see them coming out - but of course, they had plenty of money, this - this used to happen in - in - Jermond - Jermond Street. That was the half of where the clubs were, the West End. 'Cos you see my job'd be - we'd be about f
our or five hours getting unloaded, well - we used to stand and walk around you know. But I have seen them come out - with their top hats - and their - frock coats. But they always had a taxi to take them away. And I - used to - think to myself, I'd just 
like a job like that, that would just suit me to - to - be a doorman or - or a - pageboy in an hotel. 'Cos the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 You would have liked that would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Yes, 'cos the money there then, I mean - money-used to flow terrifically up there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 You mean the tips?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Would they help people into a taxi if they were rather far gone?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 And then they'd give them a tip would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Oh yes. Harrods stores - I don't know if you've ever been - seen Harrods stores, 
got about eight - eight entrances. Right round the whole of the building. 'Cos I spent a good many years - up and down there. And all the doormen - used to each week - go to - have a - had to take their turns, because some doors - were more wealthier than
 
other doors, if you understand my meaning. They'd have to change their doors each week, that was the rule of the - of - of Harrods stores. And you'd see the lady come up in her taxi - or in her car, chauffeur driven, and he - of course he would keep a spa
c
e there and he'd help her out the carriage and - receive his - tip. And when he came out - he'd know who they were and - he - he - signal for their car to come up, and he'd wrap their - the rugs round their legs, and all that sort of thing. And - away - a
nd - other - some doors were more wealthier than others you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Was it called Hans Crescent?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Yes, Hans Crescent, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 And then there's some on the Brompton Road itself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Yes. Well - well, yes, well Brompton Road was the - was the main 
entrance really. And - they used to - they used to have to take it in turns. But - them chaps had them jobs for years. Same ones all the time 'cos we knew them. And underground there, they had terrific stores underground, spread all over the Brompton Road
 and - Knightsbridge, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12601765\charrsid2953716 all the way under there you know}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 . You could actual - literally get lost. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 That was a job you kept all the time your worked full time did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 You said at one stage you became a foreman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Yes, well - that was - he last - about the last - sixteen years, they put me in charge - of the garage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Did you remain in the union all that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Oh - what, when I took charge? No. No, they wouldn't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Did you until you took charge?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Yes. Oh yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Were you sixty when you retired?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 
Sixty-two was compulsory you see because - we went - we done the - we - we closed down. We were bought out by - a firm of Bolton and Poole's of Horwich. And - I was - foreman and chauffeur. I used to chau
ffeur for the managing director in the West End. And I've known him from a boy. And he was a - quite a good guv'nor to work for. And we were both on level - footings when we were in the car. And - he said to me at the time that we was - bought out, we'd s
o
ld out, but I'd got nothing to worry about because Bolton and Poole's said that - the firm could carry on the same as they always did do. So of course we said, well that's quite all right, because it was - they - they - it was quite a good firm to work fo
r
. And that lasted three years. And then all of a sudden they - come down and - just shut it up like that. And - our Managing Director of course got accused but he didn't know, he came back off of his holiday - and I went up there to pick him up and he sai
d to me, this is a terrible shock to me, I've just come back off my holiday - and I've got to go to Horwich. He said, and we're - we've got to shut down - all the works.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 And that was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 And that was that. But I got - a full - a full week's money - one - that's right, a full week's money for every year I worked there. L}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12601765\charrsid2953716 os}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 
t it went - I forget the clause of it now, but anyway - I came out with just three hundred pounds, free of tax, and a - a three pound a week pension. I'd worked there forty-six years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 You had thought would have worked there 'til you were sixty-five had you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Was your pension the same as it would have been if you'd worked longer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Oh no - it'd have gone up, I suppose I should have got about five or six pound a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Did you get another job after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Yes, I came - when I moved here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 You moved here after that let down did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Well - you see, having - dealings with the - with - the big - the big shop, he - he had - they evidently ha
d enquired about me you see, what was going to happen to me and he spoke to me about it and he said, I hear you're going down to the coast to live. So I said, yes sir. He said, well I think you're doing the wisest thing, because he was - that time of day 
t
he Chairman of the Marshall's Federation, because they had a - the Masters had a society of their own and he was the Chairman. And - he said, I think you're doing the wisest thing because going - definitely going to be a slump, but there was but it wasn't
 
- it recovered itself. So he said, you take my advice and me. Of course when I came down here - this might shock you again, I got a job - on the forecourt of a petrol garage, up - in the village, at seven pound a week. I worked from - eight-thirty in the 
morning I started 'til six at night. Three and six an hour. That's going back - just - not quite nine years ago. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Did you think they paid you so low because of your age?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Well, I don't know you see, when I - when I retired from the - from Sil
vertown - I was in charge of course, well - all our extra hours used to - used to have to - I used to work from - half past seven in the morning 'til - never - home 'til nearly eight every night. 'Cos have to go to London you see after they'd finished wor
k
 with all the - all the work. And Saturdays the drivers would - deman - well almost demanded it, a days work because that was overtime to them. And my money when I left there was twenty-one pound a week. Then I came down here and started at - three and si
x an hour. And I - was there -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 You couldn't get anything at the Labour Exchange?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 
No. No work at all. I was silly I suppose but I was too conscientious you see, I - I - I would have got just as much on the Labour Exchange as if I was at work. And 
the I - left there - and got a job - Essex Electrical service - for eight pound a week. Driving a van. All over the place, from - nine o'clock 'til - six o'clock at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Five day week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Yes, five day week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 And no overtime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 No overtim
e. And then - I got a - I got another job - offered me for fifteen pound a week but it was about a few months before I was sixty-five wasn't it. And - he was a London garage - chap. He really wanted me - badly but - I said I would - much rather do part ti
m
e when I was sixty-five you see. And I told them over there I was going to leave. But I wanted part time work. So they - increased me money from - I think I got nine pound then - they increased my money from nine pound a week to ten pounds ten. So I staye
d
. Because they promised I could have - a part time job. That would be in 19 - when I was - 1964. Well I got a rise - that - that - my money then was five and six an hour, and that's still all I get over there now. But won't hear of me have - giving me a r
ise.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Do you think that's usual round here for the kind of work you're doing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 
Yes. Yes. And I - and - and the thing is you see - now I've just queried this. No we got an increase on our State pension. Last week. I immediately had a letter from the
 - income tax people to say my - code number'd altered. I worked - twenty-three hours last week, normally my money would be five pounds ten. So I worked the - twenty-three hours and my money was six pounds - some odd pence. And - my income tax jumped up e
ighteen shillings.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Because of the pension going up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Because of the pension going up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 It's put together and taxed as an income?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Oh yes. So out of that - thirty-four - well I'm going back to pence now, thirty-four shillings increase - t
