No, my mother wouldn't let me go you see, she said - no, once you go up there that'll be the end of it, you won't want to know me. 'Cos it was in - Kingston you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 She thought shed kind of lose you if you went there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Were you sorry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Well no, not really, I - I wasn't all - that - impressed, but I would have liked - loved to have had a go at it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Was it a very good trade to take up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Oh yes. Definitely. Yes, definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 You were a member of the Transport and General Workers union, were you an active member did you go to meetings and that type of thing?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Oh yes - yes, I want to meetings. And - used to have these b
ig meetings at different cinemas them days. And I remember one particular meeting we went to - you see - and the Transport and General Workers - union, them days were choosy and bus drivers - were always the cream of the - of the union. So they always fou
g
ht to get the bus drivers the best money. The ordinary - transport drivers, they didn't worry about, and - and there was ructions up there that particular Sunday morning. So - when - I was promoted to foreman - I was asked to give my union up which I - I 
gladly did because I wasn't - I wasn't hundred percent with 'em you see because they - they was too much one sided about it with 'em.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Too much looking after the bus drivers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Yes, well apart from that - they used to - congregate in - pubs and - r
estaurants and - to my mind they - they - they had jolly good jobs on our money. You see -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 You went on the staff to become a chauffeur?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Oh yes. Yes, because -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Was that monthly pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 No, not then, no, it wasn't - not them days. But - yo
u was a - you had quite a good position you know, you was recognised as - paid for all holidays, and - pretty well - what I said - was the law in regard - in regards to transport.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 When you were at work did you feel that there was a division interest a
mong workers, did you feel there was a big different between craftsmen and non-craftsmen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 
Oh - yes. Now this is going back a good many years. When I was a boy - of sixteen - I worked as a - I told you, as a rivet carrier. But I used to have to go and
 - work with what they call - me platers. This is something similar to what you get now in the shipyards. Which was like a shipyard.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12601765\charrsid2953716  And - they all joined the Boil}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 ermakers Union, I can remember so well. And on Saturday mornings it used to be one of my high
lights, I used to love cleaning, and I used to clean all their tools, all the boys used to have to do it, that's the - tape measures and the - rules and the squares and everything you polished up and then greased. But once they joined the union - I had to
 
go to the shop steward and get permission to handle them tools. Wouldn't allow me to touch 'em otherwise. And yet prior to that - I could have - I could do - handle 'em just as I liked. In fact I used to do quite a bit of - of their work, what they call -
 in the infancy of joysticking you see that was easier but I - I - I'd have been slowly trained as a plater. But of course when the shop - closed shop business came out well that put a - stop to it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 That was very skilled work was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Oh yes, yes, and they were the - the cream of the - of the - factory they were. What they said went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Did they mix in with everybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Oh yes, they mixed in with everybody. This happened in my - days and it happened in my father's days. When we had a bank hol
iday - they never went to work on a Tuesday. Because - they'd all go - at work - they'd go in, and the boilermakers would have a bit of a meeting and decide - oh no, they won't have - go to work today. We'll have another day off. So - everybody had to go 
home. And wasn't paid for it. You see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Everyone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 
Everybody in the factory - had to go home. So - that became a law. In the end, that we never did work Tuesdays. So when I was on the transport - Transport and General Workers Union - got us - pay 
for Bank Holidays such as Good Friday, Easter Monday. But Saturday we were out and Tuesday we were out, but that - day and a half I was short. But I didn't mind, I was single so it suited me. But - but it - it used to affect - the people in the workshops 
because they got no pay at all, so they used to be Friday, Saturday, Monday and Tuesday short - of a weeks money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 All because of the boilermakers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Yes. 'Course that was a - that was a - a law made by the unions and of course - up 'til - oh - only
 a few years ago before ever it was altered.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Do you remember a lot of people being absent on Monday at work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 No. No. No. No, they couldn't really afford it. A lot - a lot of hard drinkers amongst them. Oh yes. Yes, a lot of hard drinkers. I've s
een 'em come to work - Monday morning drunk - from Sunday night. Parties. Come into work drunk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Did they manage to do their work then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 No, they had to be hid. To recover.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Did the managers walk around much and see what was going on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Oh yes. Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 They didn't leave it all to the foremen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 No. When - well both of my work managers that I worked under there were tartars. Both of 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Were they too harsh do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Well - my second manager - was a - type of m
an that was - he was harsh and - he was an old Victorian that - you was a worker and a worker you'd got to remain. Well - I worked in the garage, and - the firm was called Moreland Haynes. Well Mr Hayne - was the second partner, he had all the - he had al
l the interest in the garage, and he looked after us. And he was a real good old - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10767064\charrsid2953716 tuff}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 
. And this works manager didn't agree with him, so you see - what he done good for us - the works manager used to penalize us for. And when the - second world war come along - we were the parent firm on the baile}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10767064\charrsid2953716 y}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716  bridge. And when they mean parent firm that means \{ILLEGIBLE\}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10767064\charrsid2953716 the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716  bailey bridge and it was to their discretion who they sub-contracted out all round the South of England to get the bridges built - as quick as poss
ible, see, so everybody done a little bit - but we were the main ones, we used to have to go out and gather these and fetch 'em back. Well - I've known a time that - they were crying out for labour inside the works - 'cos we couldn't get them, we used to 
h
ave college boys and students come in there. And - out of a - a month's - out of one month I've had sufficient petrol to drive my wagon for a fortnight. And the second fortnight I'd had nothing to do. Only kick me heels around in the garage and help - to 
-
 maintain the other vehicles or the - or the cars - with my foreman. And I had the biggest wagon you see and used to do all the principle work. But - a fortnight's - supply of petrol - and I'd be finished. And when I volunteered to go up - into the factor
y
 - of a night, 'cos you used to work - they used to work from half past five to eight o'clock you see on all this urgent work. And all day Saturday, all day Sunday. And he would not hear of it. 'Til - 'til - towards the end of the war, and there were wome
n
 coming out of there, 'cos you used to go through a clock house you see, and clock off - and I'd be clocking off at five o'clock at night - and some of these women'd come through and look - take their card out and say - cor - look - to other one, ten poun
d, that's all I've earnt. And I was getting five guineas. And got a family.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 How were they getting ten pounds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Piece work. And welding. Yes, piecework on Welding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 And they wouldn't let you change?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 I didn't want to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10366171\charrsid2953716 change, I wanted to - fill my bu}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 cks}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10366171\charrsid2953716  t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 
he hours up there because I knew - once I got up there at piecework I'd earn some extra money. Well - funny enough - the - the - the chap that was made yard foreman, we'd come - grown up from boys - you see, because there was a lot of us bo
ys in there that had all got promoted and he was the yard foreman he got made, and I said to him - he was going round giving orders to stop at eight o'clock, and I said - yes, I'll stop 'til eight. He said, I wish you would Fred. I said, well I - well I h
a
ven't - I said, I'd come up there willingly. He said, right, I'll see the guv'nor, Mr Elliot, that was the works manager. And the next day he came to me and he said he - he won't have it. He won't hear of it. He said, when - I mentioned about the garage c
o
ming up there, 'cos there was more than there was four or five of us, at times, he said, you're treading on thin ice. If you have them you're going to have trouble. But he said, I'll have another work with him. And eventually he had to eat humble pie, the
 
works manager, came down to me and he said, if you go up there today - he said, would you - demand any extra money, in regards to - doing - what you're getting now? So I said, no sir. I said - I - I he said you'll go on piecework. I said, well that's all 
I
 went. And that was the start. And I think I went up there about - last four weeks of the war - and I had m what do they call it now, the - post war credit because them day they entered in - introduced a - a - instead of paying income tax - you paid extra
 money you was being stopped that went as post war credit. Well my post war credit when I was sixty-five \{ILLEGIBLE\}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7415895\charrsid2953716 .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 
 Three pound ten. Oh some of my pals had a couple of hundred pound to come.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 But why did he take that attitude towards you for so long 
that works manager, because he was jealous of the way the transport people were looked after?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Looked after, that's it, you've got it, yes. You see. He tried to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Undermine you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Oh he tried to - get rid of the lot of us and have what they c
all sub-contract. See, that'd be - put out to a firm of contractors with vehicles and come in and do the work. And then we'd all be - all be redundant. But - he couldn't do it you see - the - the the heads wouldn't allow him, but that was his attitude.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Had he worked himself up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 
No, he came there. Actually - 'course we had a lot of dealings with him 'cos he had a car. He'd had his car, he'd fetch it in the garage and you'd have to work on that. You see. Oh he wouldn't pay, no, you got paid as your
 - for your work's money, it - that was just a - a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Was it his own private car?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 He was running a private car, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 And you were expected to maintain it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Oh, clean it and maintain it, yes, we often maintained it. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Didn't he give you a tip or something for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 
He never did me. They did do but - it depend on whatever there was done. Because I can remember one particular driver, he was a grand old chap, he'd been there donkey's years, worked with my father - he said to t
he foreman, the state I've got into to, on his car all day today - he said, he hasn't been decent enough to - to give me a drink. He said, and when I go home tonight I've got to go and have a bath. And the next day he came in and he said - here - he said,
 
here you are Hutchins, here's a pound, you can go and buy yourself some soap and have a good bath now. So what - garage foreman had told him. Weren't - wasn't telling tales on him, he told him so as he could get that. And that was the nasty remark. And th
e old boy nearly - said, I nearly told him what he could do with that pound note. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 
Did you feel that the employers and the workers had different interests, a different outlook, or did you feel that there was some unity between them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 What, in regards to -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 
Did you feel the employers were in one camp as it were and the workers in another and each had to try and get what they could type of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Well - yes, they were like that but - you see, I'd had such a lot of dealings with 'em and
 - and - I knew that it was entirely different. The - the guv'nors were - entirely the same level as themselves if they were amongst them. Always were. And I've had some shocking rows - over that - with different chaps that's worked - inside. That - there
 they want their blood, they didn't used to get their blood because I reckon they, they got - they had quite a good job, easy job. It was - never was a - a - a slave firm, never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 But did a lot of people disagree with you on that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Oh quite a few, 
oh yes. I mean - how many firms - for years and years - you'd go to work at half past seven, and nobody would turn a - do anything 'til eight o'clock. They'd be making tea and all that sort of thing. Then they'd start work at eight. And always - shut down
 at quarter past twelve for half past twelve dinner. And - and they never worried 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 That was unusual then was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Oh yes, it was those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 What about the top brass themselves, did they work hard themselves do you think or no?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Well
 - they did, they - they - they - done quite a lot of work and - they had - huge great drawing offices and - I used to have to go up there and they'd be there seven and eight o'clock at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Not manual work though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Oh no, it was all office work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14497874 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 But they put in quite a lot of hours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2099306 FK  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6825497\charrsid2953716 Oh yes, I - I've been there at half past seven in the evening and they've been there.
